article.headline: Mercury winners of six of last seven
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- It was a night to remember for Kamila Vodichkova,
who couldn't recall ever having such a hot shooting hand.

Vodichkova scored a career-high 24 points on 10-of-11 shooting --
making her first 10 -- to lead the Phoenix Mercury to a 77-60 win
Tuesday night over the Los Angeles Sparks for their sixth win in
the last seven games.

"If I've had, I don't remember it," Vodichkova said when asked
if she had ever shot as well as she did Tuesday night.

Her 10-for-10 start is the best start in league history,
according to the Elias Sports Bureau. The 10-for-11 night also is
the second-best shooting night in league history and a Mercury
franchise record.

"I spoiled my percentage," the sixth-year Czech player said of
her only miscue, a missed layup with 7:37 remaining.

Vodichkova also made 4-of-6 free throws, grabbed six rebounds
and overshadowed the league's leading scorer, Los Angeles' Chamique
Holdsclaw.

Holdsclaw scored 16 points, three under her average, but 10 of
her points were in the first half.

"We worked hard on defense so I think our offense came from
there," Vodichkova said. "We dominated the boards. Once we
dominate the boards, the game is ours."

Lisa Leslie, the league's seventh-leading scorer at 15 points a
game, had just eight points, leaving with 9:41 left after injuring
her left knee on an errant pass.

Sparks officials said she was scheduled to have the knee
examined Wednesday.

The loss for Los Angeles (11-10) was its second in the last
three games.

"We couldn't get into anything offensively because they did a
great job of switching," Holdsclaw said. "They played solid
defense and knocked down open shots. They shot as well as I've seen
any team shoot all year."

Diana Taurasi added 16 points and six assists for the Mercury
(9-12).

"Flat out awesome," Phoenix coach Carrie Graf said of
Vodichkova, acquired as a free agent in the offseason after
starring for the WNBA champion Seattle Storm last season. "(She)
sets the standard for us defensively with her persistence on the
boards. To go 10-of-11 against a team with size like that is
monumental."

Phoenix led by as much as 28 in earning its second win over Los
Angeles in three tries this season.

Coming into the season, the Mercury had one win in 20 meetings
with Los Angeles dating back to 1999 and had never beaten the
Sparks by more than 14 points in franchise history.

Vodichkova scored 16 points on 8-for-8 shooting to lead Phoenix
to a 41-29 halftime advantage as the Mercury made 16 of 28 shots
from the field.

Phoenix went on a 17-6 run to open up a 14-point lead,
outrebounding the Sparks 17-9 in the process.
